<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much storage does a RAW photo take?", answer: "RAW file size depends on megapixels and bit depth. A 24MP camera produces RAW files of approximately 25-30 MB (14-bit). A 45MP camera produces RAW files of approximately 45-60 MB. Compressed RAW formats (like Sony's lossless compressed) are roughly 40-60% of uncompressed RAW size." },
  { question: "How many photos can fit on a 64GB memory card?", answer: "At 24MP: approximately 2,600 JPEG files, 2,100 RAW files, or 1,400 RAW+JPEG pairs. At 45MP: approximately 1,400 JPEG files, 1,100 RAW files, or 740 RAW+JPEG pairs. Actual numbers vary by scene complexity, as more detailed scenes produce larger files." },
  { question: "Should I shoot RAW or JPEG?", answer: "RAW preserves maximum image data for post-processing flexibility but uses 3-4 times more storage than JPEG. JPEG is pre-processed and compressed, using less storage but offering less editing latitude. Many professionals shoot RAW+JPEG: RAW for keepers and JPEG for quick sharing." },
  { question: "How much storage do I need for a wedding shoot?", answer: "A typical wedding generates 3,000-5,000 photos. At 24MP shooting RAW+JPEG, budget approximately 100-150 GB. At 45MP, budget 200-300 GB. Many wedding photographers carry at least 256 GB of card capacity and back up to a laptop during the event." },
  { question: "How do HEIF files compare to JPEG in size?", answer: "HEIF (High Efficiency Image Format) files are typically 30-40% smaller than equivalent quality JPEG files while maintaining similar or better image quality. HEIF is used by default on newer iPhones and is supported by many modern cameras. Not all software supports HEIF editing." }
]) %>

